You can watch nested values in an `object` as shown in the [docs][1] use a *dot-like-string* notation.

```vue
var vm = new Vue({
  data: {
    e: {
      f: {
        g: 5
      }
    }
  },
  watch: {
    // watch vm.e.f&#39;s value: {g: 5}
    &#39;e.f&#39;: function (val, oldVal) { /* ... */ }
  }
})

```

To my knowledge you **CANNOT** do this with arrays (i.e. `array[0]`) because the reference my shift or be removed. I think the best way to do what you want is to compare the `newValue` and `oldValue` in the watcher [handler][2] function if the whole array changes.

```vue
// from vuejs docs
watch: {
  // whenever question changes, this function will run
  question: function (newQuestion, oldQuestion) {
    this.answer = &#39;Waiting for you to stop typing...&#39;
    this.debouncedGetAnswer()
  }
},
```


  [1]: https://vuejs.org/v2/api/#watch
  [2]: https://vuejs.org/v2/guide/computed.html?#Watchers

